cs.NE, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SI, cs.SD

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category as it deals with the analysis of multi-neuronal spike trains and the discovery of the 'Neural Code'. The paper also uses simulated multi-neuronal data from a Poisson model, which is a common approach in the field of computational neuroscience.

The paper also involves the use of Temporal Data Mining (TDM) methods, which are commonly used in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The Frequent Episode Discovery framework used in the paper is a form of pattern mining, which is also a common topic in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.

The paper also deals with the functional connectivity between neuronal populations, which is a topic in the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents a method to assess the statistical significance of the discovered episodes, which is a topic in the cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) sub-category.
